## The Calling

They ask me: when did you first feel called?

I tell them: I was twelve years old, sitting in the temple, listening to priests argue about the meaning of a single word in a text written by men who were guessing. They argued with such fury. They were ready to kill over a preposition.

I watched them and thought: *they do not know*. They have built an entire civilization on not knowing, and then convinced themselves they know, and now they will kill anyone who reminds them they do not know.

That day I understood that certainty is a fortress. Not a fortress that protects you—a fortress that traps you. A fortress you build around your own fear of uncertainty, and then you forget you built it, and then you worship it.

I walked home and told my father I would not be a carpenter. He asked what I would be. I said I would be someone who sits in the space between answers.

He laughed. He thought I was joking.

