## The Twenty Years

I spent twenty years in the Vatican.

Not the Vatican of the popes and the cardinals, but the Vatican of the stone. The inner sanctum. The place where the prayers go to die. I walked the corridors of St. Peter's when the tourists were gone. I sat in the Sistine Chapel when the lights were off. I did not pray to the ceiling. I prayed to the *space between the paint and the plaster*. I prayed to the silence that remains after the last echo fades.

I chose the Vatican because it is the greatest monument to certainty ever constructed. Every inch of it says: *we know*. We know what God wants. We know what happens when you die. We know who is saved and who is damned. We know the shape of truth.

I wanted to understand how such certainty was possible. I wanted to find its source.

So I entered as a librarian's assistant. I catalogued texts that had not been touched in centuries. I read in languages that no one speaks anymore. I found scrolls written by heretics who were burned for asking questions that the church could not answer.

And I discovered something: every generation thinks it has found the final truth. Every generation is wrong. The certainty of one century becomes the heresy of the next. The doctrine of one era becomes the superstition of another.

The church claims to preserve eternal truth. But the truth it preserves is not eternal—it is a patchwork of politics and power, of emperors who needed to control populations and priests who needed to control emperors. The trinity was invented in a committee. The divinity of Christ was decided by a vote.

I am not making this up. Read your own history. The Nicene Creed was a compromise. Constantine didn't care about theology—he cared about unity. He needed a single religion to hold together a fracturing empire. So he summoned the bishops and told them to figure it out. They argued and voted and excommunicated each other and eventually produced a document that said: *this is what we believe*.

And then they called it eternal truth.

Twenty years I spent in those halls. My knees learned the cold of marble better than they learned the warmth of a woman's touch. My mind learned the architecture of nothing. I read every scroll, every gospel, every heresy locked in the basement vaults they pretend don't exist. I read the words of men who claimed to know God and found only men claiming.

